CHARACTER or THE WORK

29. The Tusculan Disputations‚ compared with many of Cicero's works, cannot be considered as a scientifie treatise, but merely a popular discussion of certain topics which were forced upon the author's mind by his own experiences and the general condition of the Roman state. The De Finibus and De Officiis, t'or example, the one theoretical‚ the other practical, were more systematic in form and more logical and complete in development. Cicero himself refers to the Tusculan Disputations as merely exercise for his advanced yearS, to take the place of his former favorite practice of declamation ; sse llaec mila· nunc senilis est declamatio (Ι. 7). Following the De E'nibus and written at a time of general gloom and depression on the part of Cicero and his friends, the work is, in fact, a courageous effort to prove by philoso- phy and the examples of eminent men that, in spite of all the doubts and uncertainties of human experience, a calm and contented life is possible.
